 for bestpractices and # Cookie Policy Page

## Overview
Create a self-contained, accessible Cookie Policy Page that clearly explains cookie usage, defines cookie types, and provides user-facing controls to manage consent. The page should be visually aligned with the project's design system (soft pastels, rounded UI, approachable typography) and integrate with the app’s global consent state when applicable. Ensure robust runtime safety, especially around data handling, API responses, and array operations.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A dedicated policy page explaining what cookies are, how this app uses cookies, what types of cookies are employed (essential, analytics, advertising), and how users can manage their consent (toggle controls, Save Preferences, Revoke Consent).

Goals:
- Educate users about cookie usage in plain language.
- Provide granular controls for consent categories with persistent state (e.g., via localStorage or app-level consent API if available).
- Ensure accessibility (keyboard navigability, screen reader compatibility) and responsive behavior across devices.
- Offer clear actions: Save Preferences, Revoke Consent, and an informational link to the full policy.
- Handle scenarios with no connected features gracefully (no external API dependencies).

Connected features (as applicable):
- Consent state management (local persistence or backend toggle if your architecture supports it).
- Optional integration with analytics/marketing tags toggling based on consent state.
- No mandatory external API integrations; if you have a consent API, describe how to call it.

UI elements and how they should look:
- Page header with title “Cookie Policy” and subheading clarifying user control over cookie preferences.
- Explanatory sections:
  - What cookies are and why they’re used.
  - Cookie categories with toggle switches:
    - Essential
    - Analytics
    - Advertising
  - Data retention and deletion policies.
  - How to revoke or change consent.
- Interactive controls:
  - Each category should have a toggle switch (on/off) with accessible labels.
  - Save Preferences button (primary, prominent).
  - Revoke Consent option (secondary, clearly visible).
  - Informational link to the full cookie policy document or help center.
- Visual guidance:
  - Card-based sections with soft gradients or pastel cards.
  - Clear typography hierarchy: headings, subheads, body text.
  - Descriptive icons for each cookie category.
  - Confirmable feedback after saving preferences (e.g., a subtle toast or inline message).
- Responsiveness:
  - Mobile: stacked layout with toggles in a vertical list, full-width controls.
  - Desktop: two-column or card grid layout with ample white space and consistent padding.

API integrations:
- No external APIs required. If your project uses a consent management backend, outline how to persist consent via your existing endpoints; otherwise, implement client-side persistence.

## Components to Build
- CookiePolicyPage
  - Props: none or possibly a parent-provided consent state store/handlers.
  - State:
    - categories: Array<{ id: string, label: string, description: string, enabled: boolean }>
    - saving: boolean
    - savedMessage: string | null
  - Behaviors:
    - Initialize categories with defaults; respect persisted state (localStorage or global state).
    - Guard all array operations: (categories ?? []).map(...); use Array.isArray checks.
    - Persist changes on Save Preferences.
- CategoryToggle
  - Props: id: string, label: string, description: string, value: boolean, onChange: (id, value) => void
  - Accessibility: aria-checked, role="switch", keyboard accessible.
